title: For Sale:  Blued Model 65 3" with stainless hammer and trigger
postcontent:
I bought this model 65 and my wife prefers the 4" we have, so it is now up for sale. We never fired it, she just likes the balance of the 4". This is the posting from the gentleman I bought it from:

I have for sale a unique blued S&W 65-5 .357 3" barrel. It's a heavy barrel with Walnut boot grips with S&W medallions. No internal lock. Made in the early '90s. Sorry, no box or papers.

Before I get multiple emails again trying to school me that S&W never made a blued 65, allow me to explain.

You are all correct. Smith never made a blued 65; it was the model 13. I am a big Smith collector and own many S&W's, including multiple 3" models (not boasting, just how it is). I wanted a 3" model 13, but couldn't find one for the longest time. After speaking with a master gun restorer, he mentioned that there is a new "hot bluing" process designed for stainless. To his knowledge, or mine, we have never seen or heard of a blued stainless gun, but I was curious. Keep in mind, when I called S&W about this, they said that was impossible, and couldn't be done (this is why S&W didn't blue it!). So, I purchased another 65 and took it to my guy to see if this would work. The gun you see before you is the result. It turned out beautiful. Only three things wouldn't blue: the trigger, hammer, and case ejector. Now this gun is the best of both worlds, a 3" revolver that is blued, but corrosion resistant due to the stainless. Also, worth noting, this process isn't permanent. By that I mean the bluing can be removed, and you have a stainless gun back. I installed a new pair of Altamont boot grips on it, and added it to the collection. I hope everyone is now satisfied.

So, with that being said, I'm looking for $650 firm. If the ad is still up, gun is still available. Thank you,
